@node Desc "Description"

%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
%                          Description                             %
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%


DuraQWK is a very basic QWK bundler for DLG.  I wanted to get the bare
bones version working first before I started to add the "nice" stuff.

It will create QWK packets and handle reply packets, however, it
currently does not support private or netmail message areas.

Requires DLG Professional v1.1 and AmigaDOS v2.04+
@endnode

@node Instal "Installation"

%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
%                           Installation                           %
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%


Create a directory in DOORS: called DuraQWK.  Place DuraQWK and the
DuraQWK.CFG file into this directory.  Edit the config file to your
liking.

Create two menu commands, one for packing and the other for replies.

[ 2] Executable: (path/name)   DOORS:DuraQWK/DuraQWK SCAN  (for creating)
[ 2] Executable: (path/name)   DOORS:DuraQWK/DuraQWK REPLY (for replies)
[ 5] Type:                     Executable
[10] Load type:                OVERLAY
[12] Pend messages:            YES
[13] Cli mode:                 NO
[17] Priority:                 DEFAULT

@endnode

@node Config "Configuration File"

%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
%                       Configuration File                         %
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%


Here is an explanation of the keywords supported in the configuration
file (DuraQWK.CFG).  Keywords marked as '[REQUIRED]' must be provided
or else DuraQWK will not run.

BBSNAME [MAX 30 characters]
- The name of your BBS

LOCATION [MAX 30 characters]
- BBS's city, state/province, country

BBSPHONE [MAX 20 characters]
- Your BBS's phone number, including area code

SYSOP [MAX 35 characters] [REQUIRED]
- The sysop's name

BBSID [MAX 8 characters] [REQUIRED]
- The BBS ID is a 1-8 character word that identifies your BBS in the
  QWK packets.  This id is also used to name the packets.

MAXMSGS [NUMBER] (DEFAULT:200)
- Maximum number of messages to pack at a time.

LOGFILE [MAX 50 characters]
- If you want a logfile, use this keyword and specify the filename
  to use.

LOGLEVEL [NUMBER]
- 0 = TERSE (All errors and messages packed info)
  5 = FULL

HELLOFILE   [MAX 50 characters]
NEWSFILE    [MAX 50 characters]
GOODBYEFILE [MAX 50 characters]
- The full filename of your HELLO, NEWS and GOODBYE text files that can be
  viewed from the offline QWK reader.  Quotes are not required (even if the
  filename has spaces in it).

CONFIRMREPLIES
- If you want the user to confirm each message that is being processed
  from the reply packet, include this keyword.  Otherwise, DuraQWK will
  process the reply packet without user intervention (unless there's
  a problem).

@endnode

@node Usage "Usage"

%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
%                             Usage                                %
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%


There are currently two modes for DuraQWK.

'DuraQWK SCAN' is used to create QWK packets.
'DuraQWK REPLY' is used to process reply packets.

You should have a menu command setup for both options.  These options
can only be used while online.


SCAN Mode
---------
Will scan each area set in the user's Global Arc Areas and check for new
messages.  If any new messages are found, will ask whether to start packing
the messages.  Packing takes place in the background so the user can
continue to use the BBS.  They will be notified when the packet is ready
and has been uploaded to their private file area.

The packet will be compressed with whatever archiver they have set in their
User Options.  If no archiver has been selected then they will be prompted
for one.

User's can have a maximum of 11 QWK packets in their file area.  The naming
convention for these packets are <BBSID>.QWK and <BBSID>.QW0 to <BBSID>.QW9

The netmail area is currently not handled and will be skipped if included
in the user's Global Arc areas.

Messages addressed to the user will have their "received" bit set and the
waitingmail.dat file will be updated.

The user's message pointers are not adjusted until after the file has been
successfully compressed and uploaded to their private file area.  This way
if an error occurs with the packing, their message pointers will not be
effected.


REPLY mode
----------
Users must upload the QWK reply packet to their private file area before
using this option.  The packet will be decompressed using whatever
archiver they have set in their User Options.  If no archiver was selected
then they will be prompted for the archiver to use.

The header for each reply message will be shown before processing.  If
'CONFIRMREPLIES' has been set in the logfile then they will have to
confirm each message before it will be processed.  The user will be
notified if there is any problems with a reply message.

If there were no problems processing all the reply messages then the
reply packet will be deleted automatically, otherwise they will be
asked whether the packet should be deleted or not.

Imported messages are ran through any SCREEN.DAT files you have setup.  Also,
the message translator is processed for these messages as well.

@endnode

